:::summary
Medieval literature encompasses the rich body of writing produced from the fall of Rome to the dawn of the Renaissance (c. 500–1500 AD) — a millennium of extraordinary creative achievement that includes the Anglo-Saxon epic *Beowulf*, Dante's *Divine Comedy*, Chaucer's *Canterbury Tales*, and the Arthurian romances. Shaped by Christian faith, Latin learning, and vernacular oral tradition, medieval literature is not a prelude to the Renaissance but a great tradition in its own right, one that modern readers return to with increasing appreciation.
:::

